It is in the &#39;bin&#39; directory within your Cantera installation folder.  
Run the script &#39;setup_cantera&#39;, which &#39;make install&#39; places in your 
home directory, to automatically add the bin directory to your path 
environment variable.  I put the command &#39;source setup_cantera&#39; in my 
login script.

&#39;ctnew&#39; is a script that generates a demo c++ program and a Makefile to 
build it, with the paths in the Makefile set up with the appropriate 
path names for your installation of Cantera.
All it really does is copy some files from the Cantera &#39;templates&#39; 
directory to your current working directory.  Type &#39;ctnew -cxx&#39; to 
generate a C++ demo, and &#39;ctnew -f90&#39; to generate a Fortran 90 demo.  
Both show how to do some of the most common operations, such as 
defining a reacting gas mixture, setting its state, computing chemical 
equilibrium, and computing its thermodynamic, kinetic, and transport 
properties.  For application programs that only require these features 
of Cantera, these demos provide a good starting point to write your own 
code.  At least that&#39;s the idea.



